==Marketing==

===Logo===
[[File:2006 FESPIC Games mascot.gif|thumb|right|"Ujang" and "Che Mek", the Chevrotain, the official mascots of the games.]]
The 2006 FESPIC Games logo is a heart-shape image which represents the spirit, passion and tradition of the FESPIC Games. The initial KL in the logo, represents Kuala Lumpur, the capital city of Malaysia as the venue of the Games, '06 represents to the year 2006, the heart shape in the '0' portrays the loving, caring and hospitality of the people of Malaysia, while the brush stroke sphere represents unity of the Malaysians.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070301024104/http://www.kl06fespicgames.com.my/kl06/default.asp?p=kl06&what=logo|url=http://www.kl06fespicgames.com.my/kl06/default.asp?p=kl06&what=logo|title=KL'06 Logo|date=10 July 2016|archivedate=1 March 2007|work=Official Website}}</ref>

===Mascot===
The official mascot of the 2006 FESPIC Games is a pair of [[mousedeer]] named "Ujang", the male one and its female counterpart, "Cek Mek". The mousedeer is a native animal in Malaysia locally known as pelanduk or kancil which is shy, but very agile and quick thinking. It is a favourite character in local folktales commonly known as "Sang Kancil", noted for its intelligence, wit, cunning feints and quick reaction to escape from all kinds of danger, especially from its enemies. The adoption of mousedeer as the games mascot is to represent the courage of the Paralympic athletes in overcoming challenges and the odds. The names of the mascots, Ujang and Che Mek, are common nicknames for local Malay youths.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070301024123/http://www.kl06fespicgames.com.my/kl06/default.asp?p=kl06&what=mascot|url=http://www.kl06fespicgames.com.my/kl06/default.asp?p=kl06&what=mascot|title=Mascot KL'06|date=10 July 2016|archivedate=1 March 2007|work=Official Website}}</ref>

==The games==

===Opening ceremony===
The opening ceremony was held on 25 November 2006 at the KLFA Stadium. The ceremony begins with the marching of the [[Malaysian Armed Forces]] along with the mascots of the games. This was followed by the firework display and the marching of the contingents of the participating nations. [[Abdullah Ahmad Badawi]], then Prime minister of Malaysia, declared the games opened. Lee Seng Chow, the blind discus throw athlete then take the oath on behalf of the athletes. Finally the torch was lit by four Malaysian paralympic athletes, Razali Jaafar, Hisham Khaironi, Choo Kam Chan and David Wang.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ww1.utusan.com.my/utusan/info.asp?y=2006&dt=1126&pub=Utusan_Malaysia&sec=Sukan&pg=su_02.htm#ixzz4FR8gBve5 |title=Sukan Fespic dibuka penuh tradisi|work=[[Utusan Malaysia]]|date=26 November 2006}}</ref>

===Closing ceremony===
The closing ceremony was held on 1 December 2006 at the KLFA Stadium. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kl06fespicgames.com.my:80/kl06/OpeningClosing.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070710064857/http://www.kl06fespicgames.com.my:80/kl06/OpeningClosing.pdf|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2007-07-10|title=Opening and closing ceremonies}}</ref>

