{{Côted'Ivoire-footyclub-stub}}

The '''Jeantaud''' was a [[France|French]] [[automobile]] manufactured in [[Paris]] from 1893 until 1907. It was the brainchild of Charles Jeantaud, a [[coachbuilder]] who built his first [[electric car]]riage in 1881. Among the vehicles he constructed was the first car to set a [[land speed record]] ({{convert|39.24|mi/h|km/h|2|abbr=on}}, driven by [[Gaston de Chasseloup-Laubat]]), as well as [[coupe]]s and [[hansom cab]]s; in these the driver sat high, and to the rear. Some cars had an unusual bevel-gear [[front-wheel-drive]] layout. From 1902 to 1904, Jeantaud offered a range of gas-engined cars similar to 1898 [[Panhard]]s.
==Specifications== The 1899 Jeantaud Duc Profilée was powered by a 36 horsepower (26.8 kilowatts) electric engine. The car weighed around 1,400 kg and transmitted its power to the rear wheels through a chain-drive gearbox. The Profilée was designed to be more aerodynamic than its older brother, featuring pointy ends on both the front and back, which allowed it to break its less pointy rival the GCA Dogcart's record top speed of 49 mph on 4 March 1899, achieving a speed of 57 mph. Its record, though, was quickly broken by the more famous [[La Jamais Contente]], the first purpose-built land speed record car, which reached 65 mph on the same day.
==References== *{{Cite book | last = Burgess-Wise | first = David | authorlink = David Burgess-Wise | title = The New Illustrated Encyclopedia of Automobiles | publisher = BookSales Inc; Rev Upd edition (May 2000) | pages = 559 | isbn = 0-7858-1106-0}}
